<dl id="n53097ag"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53097ag">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53097ag"> 97(ag)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> echelon, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53097ag"><li>FW 352.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53097ag">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53097ag">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53097ag">MS BL 47480-97v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:182 <a name="mdd5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd5.htm#n53097ag">Draft: II.3&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">And no one&mdash;not even his most fervent admirer&mdash;could say that the General&apos;s action was a wise one. Let it be understood that when the more exalted ones of the earth desire to make a tour of trenches, there is a recognised procedure for doing it. First comes the sergeant of the platoon occupying the portion of the line under inspection&mdash;experience has shown the wisdom of having the only trustworthy guide in front. Then comes the company commander, followed by the Colonel, the Staff officer and the Great One. Immediately behind, the Adjutant (taking notes), the platoon commander (partially dazed), the machine-gun officer (not essential), and the Sapper (if he&apos;s been caught by the human avalanche) advance in <mark>echelon</mark>. <small> H.C. McNeile (&ldquo;Sapper&rdquo;) <a name="SJW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SJW"><cite title="source">John Walters</cite></a> (1927) The Man-Trap, 120</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: [Army slang] Echelon: a formation of troops laid out in parallel divisions, each with its front clear of the unit in front of it. </mm> </dd></dl>
